    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37a.1"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">1</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline><note>Apr. - 1973</note></dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska 68505</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I realize you may not remember me, but I took several classes under you at the University of Missouri in the mid-1950's. I have never forgotten the help and inspiration I received from you. You always seemed to find something positive to say about my poems, no matter how they turned out. I used to visit you and your family on your farm outside <del>c</del><add>C</add>olumbia Missouri. Sometimes I would just come out there and wander around when I needed to be alone.</p> 
                
                <p>I have never really stopped writing poety, although I haven't attempted to publish anything. Recently I have put some of my poems, the ones I like best, together in a small collection and I am sending you the enclosed copy. I hope you 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37.2_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                    
                    find some you enjoy. Several are later versions of poems I wrote in your class.</p> 
                
                <p>After I left the University of Missouri, I spent several years writing full time, maintaining myself on odd jobs and temporary employment. In addition to poetry I wrote some plays and worked with a composer, writing for the musical theater. I eventually found that devoting full time to writing did not work well for me.</p> 
                
                <p>Now I am a social worker, employed as a social planner with a united fund. Poetry is the only form of writing I have remained active at, but it is difficult to make enough time for it.</p>
                
                <p>It was a <del>reall</del> real thrill to see you no<sic>on</sic> the Dick Cavette Show last year. I was pleased to <del>l</del><add>s</add>ee you looking so well and to learn that you are still working. I tried for some time to get your address and finally succeeded through a friend in Kansas City.</p> 
                
                <p>I hope this letter and my poetry reach you. I have wanted for so long, to express my gratitude for all that I have learned from you and form your work. I hope 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37a.2_0002"/>
                    
                    you continue to feel well, enjoy life and write for many years.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>With deepest affection,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Dick Lewin</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
